The article discusses the issue of religious persecution around the world, highlighting specific cases such as the persecution of the Iranian Gonabadi Sufi dervish community, the detention of Uighur Muslims in China, the ethnic cleansing of Rohingya Muslims in Burma, and the demolition of churches in Sudan. The author emphasizes that religious freedom is a fundamental human right and that the Trump administration is committed to protecting and promoting religious freedom globally. The State Department will be hosting the Ministerial to Advance Religious Freedom in Washington, D.C., where religious leaders, civil society groups, survivors of religious persecution, and delegations from foreign governments will come together to address this issue. The author calls for collaboration among all stakeholders, including civil society groups, religious leaders, and governments, to combat religious discrimination and persecution. The promotion of religious freedom, according to the author, not only benefits individuals but also contributes to the security, economic prosperity, and openness of societies. The author concludes by emphasizing the need for all countries to protect and defend freedom of religion.